T*
(Overview) Tj
T*
(Indirect speech reports what was said without repeating the exact words.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Learning Objectives) Tj
T*
(- Explain the meaning of Indirect Speech in English using accurate subject vocabulary.) Tj
T*
(- Describe the key ideas behind reported-speech changes in tense, pronouns, and time) Tj
T*
(words.) Tj
T*
(- Apply Indirect Speech to examples such as changing a direct sentence into reported) Tj
T*
(speech.) Tj
T*
(- Avoid common errors and build confidence through reported speech transformations.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Main Lesson) Tj
T*
(1. Introduction To The Topic) Tj
T*
(Indirect speech reports what was said without repeating the exact words. In a textbook) Tj
T*
(lesson, the first goal is to make the language idea clear. Students should be able to) Tj
T*
(explain what Indirect Speech means, identify where it appears in English, and describe) Tj
T*
(the main purpose of the topic without relying on memorized sentences.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(2. Core Teaching) Tj
T*
(The central focus in Indirect Speech is reported-speech changes in tense, pronouns, and) Tj
T*
(time words. This means students must move beyond the overview and understand how the) Tj
T*
(idea actually works. A strong explanation should unpack the rules, relationships, or) Tj
T*
(patterns behind Indirect Speech and show how those ideas guide correct answers. In) Tj
T*
(English, success usually depends on understanding the meaning, form, and effect that) Tj
T*
(belong to the topic.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(3. How The Idea Is Applied) Tj
T*
(A useful way to teach Indirect Speech is to connect the explanation directly to changing) Tj
T*
(a direct sentence into reported speech. That kind of language example shows students how) Tj
T*
(the topic moves from theory into use. At this stage, the learner should be able to state) Tj
T*
(the relevant rule or principle, explain why it fits the question, and then apply the) Tj
T*
(interpretation or writing method with confidence.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(4. Why Errors Happen) Tj
T*
(One common difficulty in Indirect Speech is keeping original tense and pronouns) Tj
T*
(unchanged. This matters because many learners can repeat a definition but still fail to) Tj
T*
ET
