T*
(question alone. This turns Indirect Speech into something the student can genuinely) Tj
T*
(study and understand without depending completely on a teacher.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Key Ideas To Remember) Tj
T*
(- Indirect Speech should first be understood as a language idea before it is treated as) Tj
T*
(an exam topic.) Tj
T*
(- The learner must understand reported-speech changes in tense, pronouns, and time words) Tj
T*
(because it controls how questions in Indirect Speech are answered correctly.) Tj
T*
(- A strong answer in Indirect Speech uses the correct interpretation or writing method) Tj
T*
(and explains why that method fits the task.) Tj
T*
(- Changing a direct sentence into reported speech is the type of application that helps) Tj
T*
(move the topic from explanation to mastery.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Step-By-Step Method) Tj
T*
(1. Read the question or example and identify the part connected to Indirect Speech.) Tj
T*
(2. Recall the specific rule, process, or principle behind reported-speech changes in) Tj
T*
(tense, pronouns, and time words.) Tj
T*
(3. Apply the correct interpretation or writing method step by step instead of jumping to) Tj
T*
(the answer.) Tj
T*
(4. Check the result carefully and confirm that it matches the requirement of the topic.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Examples) Tj
T*
(Worked Example 1) Tj
T*
(1. Start with an example based on changing a direct sentence into reported speech.) Tj
T*
(2. Identify the exact idea in reported-speech changes in tense, pronouns, and time words) Tj
T*
(that the question is testing.) Tj
T*
(3. Apply the correct method for Indirect Speech step by step without skipping reasoning.) Tj
T*
(4. Check the final answer and explain why it is correct.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Example 2) Tj
T*
(1. Choose a second example that still focuses on reported speech transformations.) Tj
T*
(2. Break the task into smaller parts and link each part to the rule being used.) Tj
T*
(3. Point out how to avoid keeping original tense and pronouns unchanged while solving) Tj
T*
(it.) Tj
